---
export const prerender = true;
export const yilMeta = {
  date: '2026-05-05',
  headline: "Don't Fight the Role",
  summary:
    "When Discord auto-selects @Hermes the role instead of the bot, the answer isn't a different typing habit — it's eliminating the ambiguity from the setup.",
};

import BaseHead from '@/components/BaseHead.astro';
import Header from '@/components/Header.astro';
import Footer from '@/components/Footer.astro';
---

<!doctype html>
<html lang="en">
  <head>
    <BaseHead
      title="YIL 2026-05-05 — Don't Fight the Role | Dan Denney"
      description="When Discord auto-selects @Hermes the role instead of the bot, the answer isn't a different typing habit — it's eliminating the ambiguity from the setup."
    />
    <link rel="preconnect" href="https://fonts.googleapis.com" />
    <link rel="preconnect" href="https://fonts.gstatic.com" crossorigin />
    <link
      href="https://fonts.googleapis.com/css2?family=Manrope:wght@400;500;600;700&display=swap"
      rel="stylesheet"
    />
  </head>
  <body class="bg-white">
    <main class="relative z-10 bg-white shadow-xs">
      <Header />

      <!-- Hero: full-width-statement — white canvas, HP blue chevron pair, Manrope 500 -->
      <section class="relative overflow-hidden bg-white">
        <!-- Left HP-blue chevron: "/" parallelogram on far-left edge -->
        <div
          aria-hidden="true"
          class="pointer-events-none absolute inset-y-0 left-0 w-20 bg-[#024ad8]"
          style="clip-path: polygon(30% 0%, 100% 0%, 70% 100%, 0% 100%);"
        ></div>
        <!-- Right HP-blue chevron: "/" parallelogram on far-right edge -->
        <div
          aria-hidden="true"
          class="pointer-events-none absolute inset-y-0 right-0 w-20 bg-[#024ad8]"
          style="clip-path: polygon(30% 0%, 100% 0%, 70% 100%, 0% 100%);"
        ></div>

        <div class="mx-auto max-w-5xl px-6 py-20 sm:py-28">
          <p
            class="text-xs uppercase tracking-[0.2em] text-[#636363]"
            style="font-family: Manrope, Inter, -apple-system, BlinkMacSystemFont, sans-serif; font-weight: 400;"
          >
            2026-05-05 — Yesterday I Learned
          </p>
          <h1
            class="mt-4 text-[#1a1a1a]"
            style="font-family: Manrope, Inter, -apple-system, BlinkMacSystemFont, sans-serif; font-size: clamp(2.75rem, 6vw, 4.5rem); font-weight: 500; line-height: 1.0;"
          >
            Don't Fight the Role
          </h1>
          <p
            class="mt-6 max-w-xl text-lg leading-relaxed text-[#3d3d3d]"
            style="font-family: Manrope, Inter, -apple-system, BlinkMacSystemFont, sans-serif; font-weight: 400;"
          >
            When Discord auto-selects @Hermes the role instead of the bot, the answer isn't a
            different typing habit — it's eliminating the ambiguity from the setup.
          </p>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- Quote: standalone-dark-band — bg-[#1a1a1a], large decorative ", white quote text -->
      <section class="bg-[#1a1a1a]">
        <div class="relative mx-auto max-w-5xl overflow-hidden px-6 py-20">
          <div
            aria-hidden="true"
            class="pointer-events-none absolute -left-4 -top-10 select-none text-[16rem] leading-none text-white/5"
            style="font-family: Manrope, sans-serif; font-weight: 700;"
          >
            "
          </div>
          <blockquote class="relative max-w-3xl">
            <p
              class="text-2xl text-white sm:text-3xl"
              style="font-family: Manrope, Inter, -apple-system, BlinkMacSystemFont, sans-serif; font-weight: 400; line-height: 1.0;"
            >
              The reliable fix is not a different typing habit — it's changing the setup so the
              ambiguity goes away.
            </p>
            <footer class="mt-6 flex items-center gap-3">
              <div class="h-px w-8 bg-[#024ad8]/60"></div>
              <cite
                class="not-italic text-sm text-[#636363]"
                style="font-family: Manrope, sans-serif; font-weight: 400;"
              >
                Hermes, May 5, 2026
              </cite>
            </footer>
          </blockquote>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- Consistency: pill-h2-bar header, prose layout, cloud-band bg-gray-50 -->
      <section class="bg-gray-50">
        <div class="mx-auto max-w-5xl px-6 py-20">
          <!-- pill-h2-bar: rounded-lg pill (HP badge style), h2, accent underline bar -->
          <div
            class="inline-flex items-center gap-1.5 rounded-lg border border-[#024ad8]/30 bg-[#024ad8]/8 px-3 py-1"
          >
            <span
              class="text-[10px] uppercase tracking-[0.15em] text-[#024ad8]"
              style="font-family: Manrope, sans-serif; font-weight: 600;"
            >OpenClaw</span>
          </div>
          <h2
            class="mt-3 text-[#1a1a1a]"
            style="font-family: Manrope, Inter, -apple-system, BlinkMacSystemFont, sans-serif; font-size: clamp(1.75rem, 3vw, 2.5rem); font-weight: 500; line-height: 1.0;"
          >
            Fix the Setup, Not the Habit
          </h2>
          <div class="mt-3 h-0.5 w-12 bg-[#024ad8]"></div>

          <!-- Prose: max-w-2xl, Manrope 400, line-height 1.4 -->
          <div class="mt-10 max-w-2xl space-y-5">
            <p
              class="text-base text-[#1a1a1a]"
              style="font-family: Manrope, Inter, -apple-system, BlinkMacSystemFont, sans-serif; font-weight: 400; line-height: 1.4;"
            >
              Typing @Hermes in Discord to start a thread works — sometimes. Other times Discord's
              autocomplete lands on the Hermes role instead of the Hermes bot, based on whichever
              underlying ID it happens to select in the moment. The ambiguity is invisible until the
              bot doesn't respond, which is the worst time to find out. This is a recurring pattern
              with OpenClaw.
            </p>
            <p
              class="text-base text-[#1a1a1a]"
              style="font-family: Manrope, Inter, -apple-system, BlinkMacSystemFont, sans-serif; font-weight: 400; line-height: 1.4;"
            >
              Hermes offered three ways out: make #hermes a free-response channel so no @mention is
              needed at all (recommended — least friction, since the channel is already
              bot-dedicated); rename the role from "Hermes" to something like "Hermes Access" so
              autocomplete unambiguously points to the bot; or patch Hermes to treat a role mention
              as a valid trigger. The quick fix is the free-response route.
            </p>
            <p
              class="text-base text-[#1a1a1a]"
              style="font-family: Manrope, Inter, -apple-system, BlinkMacSystemFont, sans-serif; font-weight: 400; line-height: 1.4;"
            >
              The lesson generalizes: when a tool misbehaves intermittently based on something
              outside your control, adjusting your behavior around the ambiguity is the wrong frame.
              Remove the ambiguity from the setup and the problem stops existing.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- Design Notes -->
      <section class="border-t border-gray-200 bg-gray-50">
        <div class="mx-auto max-w-5xl px-6 py-12">
          <p
            class="text-[10px] uppercase tracking-[0.25em] text-[#636363]"
            style="font-family: Manrope, sans-serif; font-weight: 400;"
          >
            Design Notes
          </p>
          <p
            class="mt-2 text-sm text-[#3d3d3d]"
            style="font-family: Manrope, sans-serif; font-weight: 600;"
          >
            YIL 2026-05-05 — Don't Fight the Role
          </p>
          <p
            class="mt-1 text-sm text-[#636363]"
            style="font-family: Manrope, sans-serif; font-weight: 400;"
          >
            Discord role vs. bot @mention ambiguity in the OpenClaw setup, told through HP's
            commercial-catalog visual language of pure white canvas and reserved electric blue.
          </p>
          <div class="mt-4 flex flex-wrap gap-3">
            <div class="flex items-center gap-1.5">
              <span class="h-3 w-3 rounded-full" style="background: #024ad8"></span>
              <span
                class="text-[10px] text-[#636363]"
                style="font-family: Manrope, sans-serif; font-weight: 400;"
                >accent-1 / text-[#024ad8] — HP Electric Blue / process</span
              >
            </div>
            <div class="flex items-center gap-1.5">
              <span class="h-3 w-3 rounded-full" style="background: #1a1a1a"></span>
              <span
                class="text-[10px] text-[#636363]"
                style="font-family: Manrope, sans-serif; font-weight: 400;"
                >accent-2 / bg-[#1a1a1a] — Ink / quote slab</span
              >
            </div>
            <div class="flex items-center gap-1.5">
              <span class="h-3 w-3 rounded-full" style="background: #0e3191"></span>
              <span
                class="text-[10px] text-[#636363]"
                style="font-family: Manrope, sans-serif; font-weight: 400;"
                >accent-3 / text-[#0e3191] — Deep Navy / supporting elements</span
              >
            </div>
          </div>
          <p
            class="mt-6 max-w-2xl text-sm leading-relaxed text-[#636363]"
            style="font-family: Manrope, sans-serif; font-weight: 400;"
          >
            This page ports HP.com's commercial-catalog visual language onto the quietest possible
            day — a Discord thread check-in with no links, no code, and no headline insight. The
            pairing is intentional: HP's system is built for systematic, unhurried catalog
            navigation, not editorial drama. A sparse entry deserves a clean, open surface. The
            page follows HP's full surface rhythm (white canvas → ink-slab quote band → cloud
            alternating band → white), with Electric Blue reserved for the two chevron decorations
            and the single section pill — at most two blue signal elements per viewport, exactly as
            the HP system specifies.
          </p>
        </div>
      </section>
    </main>
    <Footer />
  </body>
</html>
